function minMovesUnique(nums) {
    nums.sort((a, b) => a - b);
    let moves = 0;
    for (let i = 1; i < nums.length; i++) {
        if (nums[i] <= nums[i - 1]) {
            const diff = nums[i - 1] - nums[i] + 1;
            moves += diff;
            nums[i] += diff;
        }
    }
    return moves;
}
```

    1. Sort the given integer array.
2. Initialize a counter (moves) to store the minimum number of moves.
3. Iterate through the sorted array starting from the second element (i=1).
4. Check if the current element (nums[i]) is less than or equal to the previous element (nums[i-1]), if yes, then:
   a. Calculate the difference between the previous element and current element, and increment it by 1 (since we need the current element to be greater than the previous element).
   b. Increment the moves counter by the calculated difference.
   c. Update the current element (nums[i]) by adding the difference to its value (to make it unique).
5. Return the moves counter after the iteration.

